statement.p:
A function f is concave up on a subset S of the domain (usually an interval)
if for every x_1,x_2,x_3 \in S, the slope or rate of change is increasing,
x_1 \lt x_2 \lt x_3 \qquad \text{implies} \qquad \frac{f(x_2)-f(x_1)}{x_2-x_1} \lt \frac{f(x_3)-f(x_2)}{x_3-x_2}.

A function f is concave down on a subset S of the domain (usually an interval)
if for every x_1,x_2,x_3 \in S, the slope or rate of change is decreasing,
x_1 \lt x_2 \lt x_3 \qquad \text{implies} \qquad \frac{f(x_2)-f(x_1)}{x_2-x_1} \gt \frac{f(x_3)-f(x_2)}{x_3-x_2}.

